<!-- H2 -->
<Paragraph Style="{StaticResource Heading2}">Getting the Gist of Markdown's Formatting Syntax</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
This page offers a brief overview of what it's like to use Markdown.
The <!-- Hyperlink --><Hyperlink NavigateUri="/projects/markdown/syntax">syntax page</Hyperlink> provides complete, detailed documentation for
every feature, but Markdown should be very easy to pick up simply by
looking at a few examples of it in action. The examples on this page
are written in a before/after style, showing example syntax and the
HTML output produced by Markdown.
</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
It's also helpful to simply try Markdown out; the <!-- Hyperlink --><Hyperlink NavigateUri="/projects/markdown/dingus">Dingus</Hyperlink> is a
web application that allows you type your own Markdown-formatted text
and translate it to XHTML.
</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
<Bold>Note:</Bold> This document is itself written using Markdown; you
can <!-- Hyperlink --><Hyperlink NavigateUri="/projects/markdown/basics.text">see the source for it by adding '.text' to the URL</Hyperlink>.
</Paragraph>

<!-- H2 -->
<Paragraph Style="{StaticResource Heading2}">Paragraphs, Headers, Blockquotes</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
A paragraph is simply one or more consecutive lines of text, separated
by one or more blank lines. (A blank line is any line that looks like a
blank line -- a line containing nothing spaces or tabs is considered
blank.) Normal paragraphs should not be intended with spaces or tabs.
</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Markdown offers two styles of headers: <Italic>Setext</Italic> and <Italic>atx</Italic>.
Setext-style headers for <InlineUIContainer Style="{StaticResource InlineCodeStyle}">&lt;h1&gt;</InlineUIContainer> and <InlineUIContainer Style="{StaticResource InlineCodeStyle}">&lt;h2&gt;</InlineUIContainer> are created by
"underlining" with equal signs (<InlineUIContainer Style="{StaticResource InlineCodeStyle}">=</InlineUIContainer>) and hyphens (<InlineUIContainer Style="{StaticResource InlineCodeStyle}">-</InlineUIContainer>), respectively.
To create an atx-style header, you put 1-6 hash marks (<InlineUIContainer Style="{StaticResource InlineCodeStyle}">#</InlineUIContainer>) at the
beginning of the line -- the number of hashes equals the resulting
HTML header level.
</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Blockquotes are indicated using email-style '<InlineUIContainer Style="{StaticResource InlineCodeStyle}">&gt;</InlineUIContainer>' angle brackets.
</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Markdown:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>A First Level Header
====================

A Second Level Header
---------------------

Now is the time for all good men to come to
the aid of their country. This is just a
regular paragraph.

The quick brown fox jumped over the lazy
dog's back.

### Header 3

&gt; This is a blockquote.
&gt; 
&gt; This is the second paragraph in the blockquote.
&gt;
&gt; ## This is an H2 in a blockquote</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Output:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>&lt;h1&gt;A First Level Header&lt;/h1&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;A Second Level Header&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now is the time for all good men to come to
the aid of their country. This is just a
regular paragraph.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The quick brown fox jumped over the lazy
dog's back.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3&gt;Header 3&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;This is a blockquote.&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;p&gt;This is the second paragraph in the blockquote.&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;h2&gt;This is an H2 in a blockquote&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;</Paragraph>

<!-- H3 -->
<Paragraph Style="{StaticResource Heading3}">Phrase Emphasis</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Markdown uses asterisks and underscores to indicate spans of emphasis.
</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Markdown:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>Some of these words *are emphasized*.
Some of these words _are emphasized also_.

Use two asterisks for **strong emphasis**.
Or, if you prefer, __use two underscores instead__.</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Output:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>&lt;p&gt;Some of these words &lt;em&gt;are emphasized&lt;/em&gt;.
Some of these words &lt;em&gt;are emphasized also&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Use two asterisks for &lt;strong&gt;strong emphasis&lt;/strong&gt;.
Or, if you prefer, &lt;strong&gt;use two underscores instead&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</Paragraph>

<!-- H2 -->
<Paragraph Style="{StaticResource Heading2}">Lists</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Unordered (bulleted) lists use asterisks, pluses, and hyphens (<InlineUIContainer Style="{StaticResource InlineCodeStyle}">*</InlineUIContainer>,
<InlineUIContainer Style="{StaticResource InlineCodeStyle}">+</InlineUIContainer>, and <InlineUIContainer Style="{StaticResource InlineCodeStyle}">-</InlineUIContainer>) as list markers. These three markers are
interchangable; this:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>*   Candy.
*   Gum.
*   Booze.</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
this:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>+   Candy.
+   Gum.
+   Booze.</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
and this:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>-   Candy.
-   Gum.
-   Booze.</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
all produce the same output:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Candy.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Gum.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Booze.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Ordered (numbered) lists use regular numbers, followed by periods, as
list markers:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>1.  Red
2.  Green
3.  Blue</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Output:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Red&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Green&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Blue&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
If you put blank lines between items, you'll get <InlineUIContainer Style="{StaticResource InlineCodeStyle}">&lt;p&gt;</InlineUIContainer> tags for the
list item text. You can create multi-paragraph list items by indenting
the paragraphs by 4 spaces or 1 tab:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>*   A list item.

    With multiple paragraphs.

*   Another item in the list.</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Output:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;A list item.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;With multiple paragraphs.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Another item in the list.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;</Paragraph>

<!-- H3 -->
<Paragraph Style="{StaticResource Heading3}">Links</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Markdown supports two styles for creating links: <Italic>inline</Italic> and
<Italic>reference</Italic>. With both styles, you use square brackets to delimit the
text you want to turn into a link.
</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Inline-style links use parentheses immediately after the link text.
For example:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>This is an [example link](http://example.com/).</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Output:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>&lt;p&gt;This is an &lt;a href="http://example.com/"&gt;
example link&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Optionally, you may include a title attribute in the parentheses:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>This is an [example link](http://example.com/ "With a Title").</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Output:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>&lt;p&gt;This is an &lt;a href="http://example.com/" title="With a Title"&gt;
example link&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Reference-style links allow you to refer to your links by names, which
you define elsewhere in your document:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>I get 10 times more traffic from [Google][1] than from
[Yahoo][2] or [MSN][3].

[1]: http://google.com/        "Google"
[2]: http://search.yahoo.com/  "Yahoo Search"
[3]: http://search.msn.com/    "MSN Search"</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Output:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>&lt;p&gt;I get 10 times more traffic from &lt;a href="http://google.com/"
title="Google"&gt;Google&lt;/a&gt; than from &lt;a href="http://search.yahoo.com/"
title="Yahoo Search"&gt;Yahoo&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href="http://search.msn.com/"
title="MSN Search"&gt;MSN&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
The title attribute is optional. Link names may contain letters,
numbers and spaces, but are <Italic>not</Italic> case sensitive:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>I start my morning with a cup of coffee and
[The New York Times][NY Times].

[ny times]: http://www.nytimes.com/</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Output:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>&lt;p&gt;I start my morning with a cup of coffee and
&lt;a href="http://www.nytimes.com/"&gt;The New York Times&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</Paragraph>

<!-- H3 -->
<Paragraph Style="{StaticResource Heading3}">Images</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Image syntax is very much like link syntax.
</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Inline (titles are optional):
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>![alt text](/path/to/img.jpg "Title")</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Reference-style:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>![alt text][id]

[id]: /path/to/img.jpg "Title"</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Both of the above examples produce the same output:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>&lt;img src="/path/to/img.jpg" alt="alt text" title="Title" /&gt;</Paragraph>

<!-- H3 -->
<Paragraph Style="{StaticResource Heading3}">Code</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
In a regular paragraph, you can create code span by wrapping text in
backtick quotes. Any ampersands (<InlineUIContainer Style="{StaticResource InlineCodeStyle}">&amp;</InlineUIContainer>) and angle brackets (<InlineUIContainer Style="{StaticResource InlineCodeStyle}">&lt;</InlineUIContainer> or
<InlineUIContainer Style="{StaticResource InlineCodeStyle}">&gt;</InlineUIContainer>) will automatically be translated into HTML entities. This makes
it easy to use Markdown to write about HTML example code:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>I strongly recommend against using any `&lt;blink&gt;` tags.

I wish SmartyPants used named entities like `&amp;mdash;`
instead of decimal-encoded entites like `&amp;#8212;`.</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Output:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>&lt;p&gt;I strongly recommend against using any
&lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;blink&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt; tags.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I wish SmartyPants used named entities like
&lt;code&gt;&amp;amp;mdash;&lt;/code&gt; instead of decimal-encoded
entites like &lt;code&gt;&amp;amp;#8212;&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
To specify an entire block of pre-formatted code, indent every line of
the block by 4 spaces or 1 tab. Just like with code spans, <InlineUIContainer Style="{StaticResource InlineCodeStyle}">&amp;</InlineUIContainer>, <InlineUIContainer Style="{StaticResource InlineCodeStyle}">&lt;</InlineUIContainer>,
and <InlineUIContainer Style="{StaticResource InlineCodeStyle}">&gt;</InlineUIContainer> characters will be escaped automatically.
</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Markdown:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>If you want your page to validate under XHTML 1.0 Strict,
you've got to put paragraph tags in your blockquotes:

    &lt;blockquote&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;For example.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/blockquote&gt;</Paragraph>

<!-- Paragraph -->
<Paragraph>
Output:
</Paragraph>

<!-- CodeBlock -->
<Paragraph>&lt;p&gt;If you want your page to validate under XHTML 1.0 Strict,
you've got to put paragraph tags in your blockquotes:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;blockquote&amp;gt;
    &amp;lt;p&amp;gt;For example.&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;/blockquote&amp;gt;
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;</Paragraph>
